WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.410 --> 00:00:02.680
PRESENTER: Good afternoon,
everyone.

00:00:02.680 --> 00:00:04.800
Authors at Google New York
is pleased today

00:00:04.800 --> 00:00:06.170
to welcome Jon Ronson.

00:00:06.170 --> 00:00:08.118
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:08.118 --> 00:00:10.070
JON RONSON: Hello.

00:00:10.070 --> 00:00:11.560
Hi.

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:15.210
So "The Psychopath
Test." It began--

00:00:15.210 --> 00:00:19.030
I was at a friend's house, and
she had on her shelf a copy of

00:00:19.030 --> 00:00:22.400
the DSM manual, which I'm
sure you all know about.

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:25.560
It's the manual of
mental disorders.

00:00:25.560 --> 00:00:29.730
It started off in the '50s
as a very slim volume.

00:00:29.730 --> 00:00:33.050
There were very few mental
disorders in the '50s.

00:00:33.050 --> 00:00:37.460
And then it grew and grew and
grew, and it's currently 886

00:00:37.460 --> 00:00:40.900
pages long, and it lists every
known mental disorder.

00:00:40.900 --> 00:00:45.780
And there's currently 374
mental disorders.

00:00:45.780 --> 00:00:47.930
So I was leafing through the
book, wondering if I had any

00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:52.400
mental disorders, and it turns
out that I've got 12.

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:54.970
I've got generalized anxiety
disorder, which frankly, I

00:00:54.970 --> 00:00:56.500
didn't a book to tell me.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:00.960
I've got nightmare disorder,
which is categorized if you

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:05.150
have recurrent dreams of being
pursued or declared a failure.

00:01:05.150 --> 00:01:08.870
And all my dreams involve
people pursuing me and

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:10.790
declaring me a failure.

00:01:10.790 --> 00:01:14.270
I've got a parent-child
relational problems, which I

00:01:14.270 --> 00:01:16.690
blame my parents for.

00:01:16.690 --> 00:01:18.210
I've got malingering.

00:01:18.210 --> 00:01:21.061
And I think it's actually
probably quite rare to have

00:01:21.061 --> 00:01:24.100
malingering and generalized
anxiety disorder,

00:01:24.100 --> 00:01:25.420
but there you go.

00:01:25.420 --> 00:01:27.170
I've got both.

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:30.890
The new edition, as I'm sure
you'll know, is about to come

00:01:30.890 --> 00:01:33.230
out in May, and they've just
announced some of the new

00:01:33.230 --> 00:01:34.950
disorders that are going
to be in there.

00:01:34.950 --> 00:01:36.890
Intermittent explosive
disorder.

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:39.660
There's a version of it
in the current DSM-IV.

00:01:39.660 --> 00:01:43.980
But now I met the head of the
new DSM a couple of weeks ago,

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:49.250
and I said to him, OK, if you
break a bottle against a wall

00:01:49.250 --> 00:01:53.930
twice in a year in anger, does
that mean you've got

00:01:53.930 --> 00:01:55.930
intermittent explosive
disorder?

00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:57.195
And he said, yes.

00:01:57.195 --> 00:01:58.760
So there you go.

00:01:58.760 --> 00:02:01.050
Also, they've been thinking
about putting internet

00:02:01.050 --> 00:02:03.980
addiction into the new DSM.

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:07.660
But now they've decided to put
it into the appendix, which is

00:02:07.660 --> 00:02:09.740
the graveyard of mental
disorders.

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:12.970
Which actually, I'm kind of
pissed off about, because the

00:02:12.970 --> 00:02:17.370
times when I've accidentally
typed my name into Google and

00:02:17.370 --> 00:02:20.010
inadvertently pressed Search,
and I found people slagging me

00:02:20.010 --> 00:02:22.980
off, I kind of like the idea of
them being declared insane.

00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:27.900
But unfortunately, internet
addiction isn't going to be a

00:02:27.900 --> 00:02:29.970
full-blown disorder.

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:32.760
Much later, by the way,
I was wondering why.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:35.270
You know, with these mental
disorders, was I much crazier

00:02:35.270 --> 00:02:36.700
than I thought I was?

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:39.320
Or maybe it's not a good idea
to diagnose yourself with a

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:42.690
mental disorder if you're not
a trained professional.

00:02:42.690 --> 00:02:44.900
Or maybe the psychiatry
profession has a kind of

00:02:44.900 --> 00:02:49.685
strange fetish to label
increasingly normal behavior

00:02:49.685 --> 00:02:50.790
as mental disorders.

00:02:50.790 --> 00:02:53.840
I didn't know which of those
things was true.

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:57.120
But I thought it was really
interesting to try and solve

00:02:57.120 --> 00:02:59.060
that mystery.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:04.180
Much later, by the way, I met
the man who turned the DSM

00:03:04.180 --> 00:03:07.010
from a pamphlet into
a brick of a book.

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:12.370
It was called Robert Spitzer,
who is now in Princeton.

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:14.450
At the time, he was
at Columbia.

00:03:14.450 --> 00:03:18.420
And Robert Spitzer's story
is that he hated Freudian

00:03:18.420 --> 00:03:23.300
psychoanalysis, because his
mother was miserable her whole

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:26.920
life, and she died unhappy,
and she'd gone to Freudian

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:30.210
analyst after Freudian analyst
and none of them helped her.

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:34.130
So he grew up with this kind
of hatred of Freud.

00:03:34.130 --> 00:03:37.560
And when he took over the
editorship of the DSM, he

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:41.370
decided that it was his destiny
to eradicate Freud

00:03:41.370 --> 00:03:44.880
from psychiatry and replace all
that sleuthing around the

00:03:44.880 --> 00:03:49.480
unconscious with checklists.

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:51.760
So he called all his like-minded
people into

00:03:51.760 --> 00:03:53.933
conference rooms at Columbia,
and he'd say, who's got ideas

00:03:53.933 --> 00:03:55.010
for the mental disorders?

00:03:55.010 --> 00:03:56.630
And people would go, oh, ADHD!

00:03:56.630 --> 00:03:58.400
And he'd go, what's
the checklist?

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:00.570
And he'd type it into
his typewriter.

00:04:00.570 --> 00:04:04.160
And that's how ADHD came to
be a mental disorder.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:08.540
And it's how bulimia came to
be in the DSM, and so on.

00:04:08.540 --> 00:04:11.630
The person who shouted the
loudest, he would listen to

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:14.245
them, and he'd type it into his
old typewriter, and there

00:04:14.245 --> 00:04:16.000
it was, sealed in stone.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.430
And I said to him, when I met
him in Princeton, a couple of

00:04:19.430 --> 00:04:24.340
years ago, I said, were there
any proposed mental disorders

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:26.320
that you rejected?

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:29.340
And he said, yeah,
there was one.

00:04:29.340 --> 00:04:32.340
Atypical child syndrome.

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:36.110
He said the problem with it
was when I asked the man

00:04:36.110 --> 00:04:39.310
proposing it what the shared
characteristics were, he said,

00:04:39.310 --> 00:04:40.410
that's very hard to
say, because the

00:04:40.410 --> 00:04:41.510
children are very atypical.

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:44.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:44.270 --> 00:04:46.800
JON RONSON: He said he was
also going to put in

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:50.240
masochistic personality
disorder, which would be for

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:52.960
women who remained in abusive
relationships.

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:55.140
But he said he got into terrible
trouble with the

00:04:55.140 --> 00:04:58.310
feminists, and so he changed
the name to self-defeating

00:04:58.310 --> 00:05:01.970
personality disorder and shoved
it in the appendix.

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:05.180
So this was much later.

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:08.590
And when I was at my friend's
house, I was wondering, well,

00:05:08.590 --> 00:05:11.620
what is this with mental
disorders?

00:05:11.620 --> 00:05:12.950
What's the issue?

00:05:12.950 --> 00:05:17.790
And so I decided to meet a
critic of psychiatry to get

00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:21.860
their view, which is how I ended
up having lunch with the

00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:23.360
Scientologists.

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:26.290
And it was a crack team
of Scientologists.

00:05:26.290 --> 00:05:27.020
This was in London.

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:28.970
They're called the CCHR.

00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:32.830
And it's their destiny
to destroy

00:05:32.830 --> 00:05:36.400
psychiatry wherever it lies--

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:39.230
probably because of difficult
relationships between L. Ron

00:05:39.230 --> 00:05:41.550
Hubbard and psychiatrists,
back in the day.

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:44.585
And I had lunch with the head
of the London branch.

00:05:44.585 --> 00:05:46.220
His name was Brian.

00:05:46.220 --> 00:05:50.600
And I said, can you prove to me
that psychiatry is a wicked

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:52.350
pseudoscience that
can't be trusted?

00:05:52.350 --> 00:05:55.300
Can you prove your
ideology to me?

00:05:55.300 --> 00:05:57.490
And he said, yes, I can
prove it to you.

00:05:57.490 --> 00:05:58.890
And I said, how?

00:05:58.890 --> 00:06:01.860
And he said, I can introduce
you to Tony.

00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:03.910
And I said, who's Tony?

00:06:03.910 --> 00:06:06.570
And he said, Tony's
in Broadmoor.

00:06:06.570 --> 00:06:08.960
And Broadmoor is Broadmoor
Hospital.

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:13.970
It was Britain's most notorious,
mythologically

00:06:13.970 --> 00:06:18.360
notorious asylum for the
criminally insane.

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:20.830
It's now called, of course,
Broadmoor Hospital.

00:06:20.830 --> 00:06:24.500
And I said, what did Tony do?

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:28.040
And Brian said, hardly
anything.

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:30.160
He beat someone up
with something.

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:34.245
But the point is, he decided to
fake madness to get out of

00:06:34.245 --> 00:06:37.620
a prison sentence, and he faked
it too well, and now

00:06:37.620 --> 00:06:39.710
he's stuck in Broadmoor.

00:06:39.710 --> 00:06:41.750
And the more he tries to
convince the psychiatrists

00:06:41.750 --> 00:06:44.290
there that he's sane, the more
they take it as evidence that

00:06:44.290 --> 00:06:45.890
he's crazy.

00:06:45.890 --> 00:06:48.720
Do you want us to get you into
Broadmoor to meet Tony?

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:50.900
So I said, yes, please.

00:06:50.900 --> 00:06:52.510
So I'm going to read a tiny
bit from "The Psychopath

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:55.890
Test," what happened when
I went to Broadmoor.

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:57.930
I got the train there.

00:06:57.930 --> 00:07:01.500
I began to yawn uncontrollably
around Kempton Park, which is

00:07:01.500 --> 00:07:04.000
what dogs also do
when anxious.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.910
And I got to Broadmoor, and I
met Brian, and we were taken

00:07:06.910 --> 00:07:11.030
through high-security gate after
gate after gate into the

00:07:11.030 --> 00:07:13.100
Wellness Center, which
is where you

00:07:13.100 --> 00:07:14.230
get to meet the patients.

00:07:14.230 --> 00:07:18.430
And it's all calming colors,
like peaches and pine.

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:21.020
And I'm going to do a little
microphone experiment of,

00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:23.550
like, leaning back a bit
and seeing if you

00:07:23.550 --> 00:07:24.080
can still hear me?

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:25.080
Is that OK?

00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:26.320
Because I was getting a--

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:27.640
great.

00:07:27.640 --> 00:07:29.150
OK.

00:07:29.150 --> 00:07:31.560
So the Wellness Center at
Broadmoor, it's all peach and

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:33.370
pine and calming colors.

00:07:33.370 --> 00:07:36.170
It looks like a kind
of travel inn.

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:41.820
And the only bold colors are the
reds of the panic buttons.

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:46.210
And Brian said to me, you know,
Tony's the only person

00:07:46.210 --> 00:07:49.460
in the entire DSPD unit to have
the privilege of meeting

00:07:49.460 --> 00:07:51.160
people in the Wellness Center.

00:07:51.160 --> 00:07:53.380
And I said, what does
DSPD stand for?

00:07:53.380 --> 00:07:56.670
And Brian said, Dangerous and
Severe Personality Disorder.

00:07:56.670 --> 00:07:59.670
And I said, is Tony in the part
of Broadmoor that houses

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:01.180
the most dangerous people?

00:08:01.180 --> 00:08:04.580
And Brian said, yeah,
isn't that insane?

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:08.070
And then the patients started
drifting in, and they're all

00:08:08.070 --> 00:08:13.240
quite overweight and wearing
sweatpants and shuffling, and

00:08:13.240 --> 00:08:15.230
they had sort of doleful eyes.

00:08:15.230 --> 00:08:18.990
And Brian whispered to me,
they're medicated.

00:08:18.990 --> 00:08:22.700
Which, to a Scientologist, is
like the worst evil in the

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:25.970
world, but I'm thinking it's
presumably a good idea.

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:30.060
And then Brian said,
here's Tony.

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:32.549
And a man was walking towards
me, and he wasn't overweight.

00:08:32.549 --> 00:08:35.030
He was in excellent physical
condition.

00:08:35.030 --> 00:08:36.270
And he wasn't wearing
sweatpants.

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:38.720
He was wearing a
pinstripe suit.

00:08:38.720 --> 00:08:41.860
It was evidently the outfit of
a man who wanted to prove to

00:08:41.860 --> 00:08:45.130
me that he was incredibly
sane.

00:08:45.130 --> 00:08:48.810
So we sat down, and I said, is
it true that you faked your

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:49.550
way in here?

00:08:49.550 --> 00:08:50.700
And he said, yeah, absolutely.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:56.510
I beat a man up in Reading,
which is just west of London.

00:08:56.510 --> 00:09:00.480
And I was on remand, and my
cellmate said, you're looking

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:02.030
at five to seven
years for this.

00:09:02.030 --> 00:09:04.530
What you have to do
is fake madness.

00:09:04.530 --> 00:09:05.550
Tell them you're mad.

00:09:05.550 --> 00:09:07.330
You'll get sent to some
cushy hospital.

00:09:07.330 --> 00:09:09.340
You'll have your own
PlayStation.

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:12.905
Nurses will bring you pizzas.

00:09:12.905 --> 00:09:14.700
So he says, so that's
what I did.

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:15.960
And I said, how to do it?

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:17.950
He said, well, I asked to see
the prison psychiatrist.

00:09:17.950 --> 00:09:20.280
And I'd just seen a film called
"Crash," in which

00:09:20.280 --> 00:09:24.500
people get sexual pleasure from
crashing cars into walls.

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:27.940
So I said to the psychiatrist,
I get sexual pleasure from

00:09:27.940 --> 00:09:29.810
crashing cars into walls.

00:09:29.810 --> 00:09:30.830
And I said, what else?

00:09:30.830 --> 00:09:34.280
And he said, oh, I told the
psychiatrist that I wanted to

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:38.200
watch women as they died,
because it would make me feel

00:09:38.200 --> 00:09:39.760
more normal.

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:41.580
And I said, where'd
you get that from?

00:09:41.580 --> 00:09:44.380
And he said, oh, from a
biography of Ted Bundy that

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:46.610
they had in the prison
library.

00:09:46.610 --> 00:09:49.090
So anyway, I faked
madness too well.

00:09:49.090 --> 00:09:50.680
They didn't send me some
cushy hospital.

00:09:50.680 --> 00:09:52.820
They sent me to Broadmoor.

00:09:52.820 --> 00:09:55.560
The minute I got here, took a
look around, asked to see the

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:56.230
psychiatrist.

00:09:56.230 --> 00:09:59.040
I said, there's been a terrible
misunderstanding.

00:09:59.040 --> 00:10:00.630
I said, how long have
you been here for?

00:10:00.630 --> 00:10:03.570
He said, well, if I had done my
time for the original GBH,

00:10:03.570 --> 00:10:05.140
I'd have got five
to seven years.

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:10.720
I've been in Broadmoor
for 12 years.

00:10:10.720 --> 00:10:14.250
It is an awful lot harder,
Tony told me, to convince

00:10:14.250 --> 00:10:17.910
people you're sane than it is to
convince them you're crazy.

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:20.700
I thought the best way to seem
normal, he said, would be to

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:24.380
talk to people normally about
normal things, like football.

00:10:24.380 --> 00:10:26.660
That's the obvious thing
to do, right?

00:10:26.660 --> 00:10:29.110
I subscribe to "New Scientist."
I like reading

00:10:29.110 --> 00:10:31.410
about scientific
breakthroughs.

00:10:31.410 --> 00:10:33.730
One time, they had an article
about how the US Army was

00:10:33.730 --> 00:10:36.370
training bumblebees to
sniff out explosives.

00:10:36.370 --> 00:10:38.880
So I said to a nurse, did you
know that the US Army's

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:42.610
training bumblebees to
sniff out explosives?

00:10:42.610 --> 00:10:45.730
Later, when I read my medical
notes, I saw they'd written,

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:49.040
"thinks bees can sniff
out explosives."

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:52.980
An then when Tony said this to
me, I thought it was probably

00:10:52.980 --> 00:10:56.180
good idea that I hadn't met any
psychiatrists when I was

00:10:56.180 --> 00:10:59.630
writing "The Men Who Stare At
Goats," which if people don't

00:10:59.630 --> 00:11:00.770
know, it's full of that stuff.

00:11:00.770 --> 00:11:04.210
It was my previous story.

00:11:04.210 --> 00:11:08.560
I was in Hawaii and I met a man
called Glenn Wheaton, who

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:12.050
was part of a secret
US military unit

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:13.930
called Project Jedi.

00:11:13.930 --> 00:11:16.490
And I said, what was
Project Jedi?

00:11:16.490 --> 00:11:19.280
And he said it was a
series of levels.

00:11:19.280 --> 00:11:20.490
And I said, what
was level one?

00:11:20.490 --> 00:11:24.100
He said, level one
was observation.

00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:25.580
You walk into a room.

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:27.360
How many chairs are
in the room?

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:30.570
The super soldier
would just know.

00:11:30.570 --> 00:11:32.040
And I said, what
was level two?

00:11:32.040 --> 00:11:34.170
He said, level two
is intuition.

00:11:34.170 --> 00:11:35.480
You're at a fork in the road.

00:11:35.480 --> 00:11:36.700
Do you go left?

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:37.940
Do you go right?

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:39.480
You go right.

00:11:39.480 --> 00:11:40.800
And I said, what was
level three?

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:44.632
And he said level three
was invisibility.

00:11:44.632 --> 00:11:49.450
And I said, that's quite
a leap from level two.

00:11:49.450 --> 00:11:51.620
I said, what, actual
invisibility?

00:11:51.620 --> 00:11:56.180
And he said, at first, but after
a while, we adapted it

00:11:56.180 --> 00:11:59.896
to just trying to find a
way of not being seen.

00:11:59.896 --> 00:12:01.205
So I said, like camouflage?

00:12:01.205 --> 00:12:02.646
And he went, no.

00:12:02.646 --> 00:12:04.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:04.620 --> 00:12:08.000
He said, level four was we had
a master sergeant that could

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.790
stop the heart of a goat just
by wanting it to stop.

00:12:12.790 --> 00:12:14.640
And I said, did he
ever manage it?

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:16.090
And he said, one time.

00:12:16.090 --> 00:12:20.810
