00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:46.010
I don't have anybody
left in the world.

00:23:46.010 --> 00:23:48.410
Anybody who ever loved me has
betrayed me and gone.

00:23:48.410 --> 00:23:49.490
I have nobody left.

00:23:49.490 --> 00:23:51.290
And I thought, well,
that's OK, then.

00:23:51.290 --> 00:23:56.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:56.200 --> 00:24:00.180
Anyway, I recounted all my
findings to Robert Hare, who

00:24:00.180 --> 00:24:01.310
was unimpressed.

00:24:01.310 --> 00:24:04.270
And he said forget about
some Haitian dictator.

00:24:04.270 --> 00:24:06.810
Forget about some guy
at Broadmoor.

00:24:06.810 --> 00:24:09.360
The big story is corporate
psychopathy.

00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:11.660
This is like the world's
biggest story.

00:24:11.660 --> 00:24:13.770
And I have to say, back then--
things have slightly changed.

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:16.150
But back then, it was true, what
Robert Hare said, that

00:24:16.150 --> 00:24:18.920
this was like a hugely important
story, but nobody

00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:20.080
was interested.

00:24:20.080 --> 00:24:24.600
Nobody cared when he told them
that it was the solution to

00:24:24.600 --> 00:24:26.210
the greatest mysteries of all.

00:24:26.210 --> 00:24:27.300
Why the wars?

00:24:27.300 --> 00:24:28.490
Why the corruption?

00:24:28.490 --> 00:24:30.480
Why the tax evasion?

00:24:30.480 --> 00:24:32.120
While all these terrible
things?

00:24:32.120 --> 00:24:33.450
Corporate psychopaths.

00:24:33.450 --> 00:24:37.050
This was Hare's contention,
that psychopathic behavior

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:39.370
will both propel you to the top
of the tree, because of

00:24:39.370 --> 00:24:43.770
the kind of person it turns you
into, and also, the system

00:24:43.770 --> 00:24:44.860
rewards it.

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:46.460
He said this was an
enormous story.

00:24:46.460 --> 00:24:47.810
Why is nobody interested?

00:24:47.810 --> 00:24:49.910
He said, you should get yourself
some corporate

00:24:49.910 --> 00:24:51.510
psychopaths to interview.

00:24:51.510 --> 00:24:52.060
And so I tried.

00:24:52.060 --> 00:24:53.740
I wrote to Bernie Madoff,
saying, can I come and

00:24:53.740 --> 00:24:55.670
interview you to find out
if you're a psychopath?

00:24:55.670 --> 00:24:57.250
And he didn't write back.

00:24:57.250 --> 00:24:58.980
So then I changed tack.

00:24:58.980 --> 00:25:01.400
I wrote to "Chainsaw" Al Dunlap,
the famous asset

00:25:01.400 --> 00:25:03.570
stripper from the '90s.

00:25:03.570 --> 00:25:06.180
I said, I believe you may have
a very special brain anomaly

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:07.310
that makes you interested
in the

00:25:07.310 --> 00:25:09.240
predatory spirit and fearless.

00:25:09.240 --> 00:25:11.060
Can I come and interview
you about your

00:25:11.060 --> 00:25:13.090
special brain anomaly?

00:25:13.090 --> 00:25:15.390
And he said, come on over.

00:25:15.390 --> 00:25:17.120
So I went to Al Dunlap's
place.

00:25:17.120 --> 00:25:20.180
Al Dunlap, if people don't know,
would go into a failing

00:25:20.180 --> 00:25:23.630
business, fire 30% of the
workforce, always with a quip.

00:25:23.630 --> 00:25:25.890
For instance, he once
told somebody--

00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:27.040
somebody once said to him,
I've just bought

00:25:27.040 --> 00:25:28.040
myself a new car.

00:25:28.040 --> 00:25:29.680
And he said, you may have a
new car, but I'll tell you

00:25:29.680 --> 00:25:32.330
what you don't have-- a job.

00:25:32.330 --> 00:25:36.010
Plus, he once threatened his
first wife with a knife, and

00:25:36.010 --> 00:25:38.480
said he always wondered what
human flesh tasted like.

00:25:38.480 --> 00:25:39.650
Plus he didn't turn
up to either of

00:25:39.650 --> 00:25:41.580
his parents' funerals.

00:25:41.580 --> 00:25:45.480
So I went to his house, which
was filled with sculptures of

00:25:45.480 --> 00:25:46.560
predatory animals.

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:48.950
It was like he was giving me
a tour of the gardens.

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:50.495
It was this grand mansion.

00:25:50.495 --> 00:25:54.100
He was going, over there, you've
got lions and tigers

00:25:54.100 --> 00:25:57.580
and more-- he was saying this
in a less effeminate way.

00:25:57.580 --> 00:26:00.665
Tigers and falcons and eagles.

00:26:00.665 --> 00:26:03.130
It was like Narnia.

00:26:03.130 --> 00:26:07.070
And then we went into his
kitchen, and it was Al and his

00:26:07.070 --> 00:26:09.420
wife Judy, and his
bodyguard Sean.

00:26:09.420 --> 00:26:11.280
And I said, you know how I
said in my email that you

00:26:11.280 --> 00:26:13.170
might have a special
brain anomaly?

00:26:13.170 --> 00:26:14.740
And he said, yeah, it's
an amazing theory.

00:26:14.740 --> 00:26:16.970
It's like "Star Trek."
You're going where no

00:26:16.970 --> 00:26:18.510
man has gone before.

00:26:18.510 --> 00:26:23.110
And I said, well, some
psychiatrists would say that

00:26:23.110 --> 00:26:25.580
this makes you [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:25.580 --> 00:26:27.290
And he went, what?

00:26:27.290 --> 00:26:28.165
And I said, a psychopath.

00:26:28.165 --> 00:26:30.790
And I've got a list in my pocket
of psychopathic traits.

00:26:30.790 --> 00:26:32.850
Can I go through
them with you?

00:26:32.850 --> 00:26:35.230
And he looked intrigued,
because what saved me

00:26:35.230 --> 00:26:35.990
was like all of us.

00:26:35.990 --> 00:26:38.370
He loved nothing more than a
mental health checklist.

00:26:38.370 --> 00:26:41.920
And he said, OK.

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:44.900
So I said, grandiose sense
of self-worth?

00:26:44.900 --> 00:26:46.990
Which I have to say would have
been a hard one for him to

00:26:46.990 --> 00:26:49.130
deny, because he was standing
underneath a giant oil

00:26:49.130 --> 00:26:51.860
painting of himself.

00:26:51.860 --> 00:26:53.970
And he said, you've got
to believe in you!

00:26:53.970 --> 00:26:56.020
And I said, shallow affect?

00:26:56.020 --> 00:26:57.670
And he said, who wants to be
weighed down with some

00:26:57.670 --> 00:26:58.930
nonsense emotions?

00:26:58.930 --> 00:26:59.620
And I said, manipulative?

00:26:59.620 --> 00:27:01.450
And he said, that's
leadership.

00:27:01.450 --> 00:27:03.220
So he basically went through
much of the checklist,

00:27:03.220 --> 00:27:06.270
redefining it as business
positives.

00:27:06.270 --> 00:27:08.500
But I have to say, something
happened to me the day I was

00:27:08.500 --> 00:27:11.050
at Al Dunlap's, which was
whenever he said something to

00:27:11.050 --> 00:27:15.400
me that was non-psychopathic, I
thought, well, I'm not going

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:18.140
to put that in my book.

00:27:18.140 --> 00:27:20.110
So he said no to juvenile
delinquency.

00:27:20.110 --> 00:27:22.070
He got accepted to West Point.

00:27:22.070 --> 00:27:25.910
He said no to many short-term
marital relationships.

00:27:25.910 --> 00:27:28.710
He's only been married twice,
and his second marriage has

00:27:28.710 --> 00:27:31.950
lasted 41 years.

00:27:31.950 --> 00:27:32.965
And all of those things.

00:27:32.965 --> 00:27:35.220
I thought, well, I'm not going
to put that in my book.

00:27:35.220 --> 00:27:37.320
And then I realized, of course,
that becoming a

00:27:37.320 --> 00:27:40.140
psychopath-spotter had turned me
a little bit psychopathic,

00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:42.840
in the way that I was desperate
to shove Al Dunlap

00:27:42.840 --> 00:27:45.390
into a box marked psychopath.

00:27:45.390 --> 00:27:49.540
Desperate to define him
by his maddest edges.

00:27:49.540 --> 00:27:52.000
And I mean, I think that's kind
of what we all do is as

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:52.680
journalists.

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:53.950
As my friend Adam Curtis
said to me, when

00:27:53.950 --> 00:27:54.880
I got back to London--

00:27:54.880 --> 00:27:56.800
he's a British documentary
maker--

00:27:56.800 --> 00:27:59.290
he said, here we travel around
the world with our notepads in

00:27:59.290 --> 00:28:02.160
our hands, and we wait
for the gems.

00:28:02.160 --> 00:28:04.780
And the gems are always be
outermost aspects of that

00:28:04.780 --> 00:28:05.890
person's personality.

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:07.250
And we're like medieval monks.

00:28:07.250 --> 00:28:11.710
We stitch together the gems and
leave the ordinary, normal

00:28:11.710 --> 00:28:14.030
behavior on the floor.

00:28:14.030 --> 00:28:17.290
And those gems are always the
things that would be defined,

00:28:17.290 --> 00:28:21.490
within the DSM, as
mental disorders.

00:28:21.490 --> 00:28:24.880
And he said, we all know that
what we do is odd--

00:28:24.880 --> 00:28:31.200
and kind of leading to a
nefarious conformity.

00:28:31.200 --> 00:28:32.840
But we don't like to
think about it.

00:28:32.840 --> 00:28:34.900
What does it say about our
own mental health?

00:28:34.900 --> 00:28:37.520
And I think Adam's right.

00:28:37.520 --> 00:28:39.440
I think that that is what
we do, as journalists.

00:28:39.440 --> 00:28:42.640
And I suppose for the last few
years, I've been trying to do

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:43.440
the opposite of that.

00:28:43.440 --> 00:28:48.390
I've been trying to not define
people by their maddest edges.

00:28:48.390 --> 00:28:50.620
And I think it's a good point,
and I'll finish here.

00:28:50.620 --> 00:28:53.235
Don't know if anybody wants
to ask me questions.

00:28:53.235 --> 00:28:56.090
And I just think, as the new
DSM's about to come out and

00:28:56.090 --> 00:28:58.550
it's going to be even bigger
than DSM-IV, there's going to

00:28:58.550 --> 00:29:02.590
be even more mental disorders
in there, I think it's

00:29:02.590 --> 00:29:05.850
probably a good time to think
about defining people by their

00:29:05.850 --> 00:29:09.920
gray areas, as opposed to
their maddest edges.

00:29:09.920 --> 00:29:11.164
Thank you very much.

00:29:11.164 --> 00:29:16.828
[APPLAUSE]

00:29:16.828 --> 00:29:18.820
JON RONSON: I don't know if
anybody's got any questions.

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:19.820
Hello.

00:29:19.820 --> 00:29:20.820
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:29:20.820 --> 00:29:21.820
[INAUDIBLE]

00:29:21.820 --> 00:29:22.320
psychopath.

00:29:22.320 --> 00:29:23.820
PRESENTER: Please come
to the microphone.

00:29:23.820 --> 00:29:25.430
JON RONSON: Oh.

00:29:25.430 --> 00:29:28.048
Yes.

00:29:28.048 --> 00:29:30.000
Like that.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:31.290
PRESENTER: Think about the
psychopathic list.

00:29:31.290 --> 00:29:33.330
I wonder if you think, from an
evolutionary perspective, that

00:29:33.330 --> 00:29:36.230
the traits that made somebody a
psychopath was giving them a

00:29:36.230 --> 00:29:39.500
competitive advantage, a
lift through evolution.

00:29:39.500 --> 00:29:41.895
And even now, in today's
messed-up society, to use your

00:29:41.895 --> 00:29:43.810
words, if you think that it
still gives them an advantage.

00:29:43.810 --> 00:29:44.110
JON RONSON: Yeah.

00:29:44.110 --> 00:29:45.780
And that's certainly
what Hare thinks.

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:49.770
And there's a new writer on the
block called Kevin Dutton.

00:29:49.770 --> 00:29:51.807
He's just brought out a book
called "The Wisdom of

00:29:51.807 --> 00:29:53.140
Psychopaths." So he
believes that.

00:29:53.140 --> 00:29:54.280
In fact, Kevin Dutton
would say that and

00:29:54.280 --> 00:29:56.260
would go one step further--

00:29:56.260 --> 00:29:58.940
and it's not a step that
I would take--

00:29:58.940 --> 00:30:02.110
which is that it's actually, we
can learn from psychopaths.

00:30:02.110 --> 00:30:02.920
It's good.

00:30:02.920 --> 00:30:05.940
We can learn coolness
under pressure.

00:30:05.940 --> 00:30:09.300
So not only is it evolutionary,
but it actually

00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:11.560
could be considered
to be positive.

00:30:11.560 --> 00:30:14.450
Which is something I don't buy,
because I think if you

00:30:14.450 --> 00:30:17.960
don't have empathy, if empathy
just literally is absent from

00:30:17.960 --> 00:30:22.600
your brain, what would always
grow in the barren landscape

00:30:22.600 --> 00:30:26.080
is, you know, malevolence, is
this is the other items on the

00:30:26.080 --> 00:30:28.290
checklists, and always
malevolent.

00:30:28.290 --> 00:30:30.840
And an Army recruiter
once told me--

00:30:30.840 --> 00:30:33.930
it's a very popular belief
that capitalism rewards

00:30:33.930 --> 00:30:35.280
psychopathic behavior.

00:30:35.280 --> 00:30:37.470
And I think that is true
to a certain extent.

00:30:37.470 --> 00:30:39.570
I think it's true in the kind
of industries where a

00:30:39.570 --> 00:30:43.890
short-term kill is beneficial,
like hedge funds, you could

00:30:43.890 --> 00:30:49.160
say, or fucking health
insurance industry.

00:30:49.160 --> 00:30:50.130
And so on--

00:30:50.130 --> 00:30:50.690
journalism.

00:30:50.690 --> 00:30:55.980
But I think in businesses where,
actually, the long term

00:30:55.980 --> 00:30:58.100
is important, it's never
going to work out.

00:30:58.100 --> 00:30:59.610
There's always going to
be a transgression.

00:30:59.610 --> 00:31:00.820
It's always going to chaos.

00:31:00.820 --> 00:31:05.820
And an Army recruiter said to
me, contrary to what certain

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:08.875
people believe, we don't want
psychopaths in our battalions.

00:31:08.875 --> 00:31:11.740
It's the last thing we want,
because they make terrible

00:31:11.740 --> 00:31:13.900
team players.

00:31:13.900 --> 00:31:14.840
