00:32:54.550 --> 00:32:57.815
I was wondering how you choose
stories, and also, how often

00:32:57.815 --> 00:32:59.970
you choose ones that
don't go anywhere?

00:32:59.970 --> 00:33:01.340
JON RONSON: Well,
I mean, often.

00:33:04.040 --> 00:33:06.770
And I find it--

00:33:06.770 --> 00:33:08.230
very hard to--

00:33:08.230 --> 00:33:11.015
you spend months and months on
Google looking for the page

00:33:11.015 --> 00:33:14.790
that nobody else has ever
found, for the story.

00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:16.430
And quite often.

00:33:16.430 --> 00:33:21.560
The most depressing one that
went nowhere, actually, was I

00:33:21.560 --> 00:33:24.580
was going to write a book about
the credit industry.

00:33:24.580 --> 00:33:28.670
I had a prophetic sense that it
was all going to collapse.

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:31.030
Because I wrote the piece in
"Lost At Sea," which is my new

00:33:31.030 --> 00:33:33.120
collection-- which
is available for

00:33:33.120 --> 00:33:36.150
sale just over here.

00:33:36.150 --> 00:33:37.895
I wrote a piece called "Who
Killed Richard Cullen?" about

00:33:37.895 --> 00:33:39.700
a man who committed suicide
because he was out of his

00:33:39.700 --> 00:33:41.300
depth with credit cards.

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:43.120
And people kept on saying
to me, you know, this

00:33:43.120 --> 00:33:43.790
is a house of cards.

00:33:43.790 --> 00:33:44.620
This isn't going to last.

00:33:44.620 --> 00:33:47.100
And I became obsessed with
writing a book about the

00:33:47.100 --> 00:33:48.220
credit industry.

00:33:48.220 --> 00:33:51.470
And I spent months and months
on it, and I failed.

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:55.690
And the reason why I failed,
the terrible truth, is that

00:33:55.690 --> 00:33:58.590
the people who I met, the people
who were coming up with

00:33:58.590 --> 00:34:00.560
the tricks to keep
people enslaved--

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:02.960
the terrible stuff
they were doing.

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:04.140
The late fees--

00:34:04.140 --> 00:34:06.460
they were boring people, and
I couldn't make them

00:34:06.460 --> 00:34:07.590
light up the page.

00:34:07.590 --> 00:34:10.100
And I'd go and meet them, and
nothing exciting would happen.

00:34:10.100 --> 00:34:12.520
And I say, in fact, in "The
Psychopathic Test," if you

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:15.090
want to get away with
wielding true

00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:17.820
malevolent power, be boring.

00:34:17.820 --> 00:34:20.580
Because journalists like
writing about colorful,

00:34:20.580 --> 00:34:22.650
engaging people.

00:34:22.650 --> 00:34:24.940
It makes us look good.

00:34:24.940 --> 00:34:28.909
So don't like Blofeld, all
monochord and ostentatious.

00:34:28.909 --> 00:34:31.000
Be boring.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:32.659
And then the next thing,
I suppose, is--

00:34:35.219 --> 00:34:37.355
OK, you've got a mystery
to solve.

00:34:37.355 --> 00:34:40.210
And I like to think my books
always start with a mystery.

00:34:40.210 --> 00:34:42.250
And the mystery in "The
Psychopath Test," I suppose

00:34:42.250 --> 00:34:42.980
there was a few of them.

00:34:42.980 --> 00:34:46.880
One of them was, is it true,
what psychiatrists say, that

00:34:46.880 --> 00:34:48.440
psychopaths rule the world?

00:34:48.440 --> 00:34:50.199
Is that true?

00:34:50.199 --> 00:34:52.320
It's a huge thing to say, and
it almost sounds like a

00:34:52.320 --> 00:34:53.780
conspiracy theory.

00:34:53.780 --> 00:34:56.090
Yet the people who say these
things are eminent.

00:34:56.090 --> 00:34:57.470
And so that's the mystery
that you leap into.

00:34:57.470 --> 00:34:59.490
And then you have to be
completely open to wherever

00:34:59.490 --> 00:35:00.930
the story takes you.

00:35:00.930 --> 00:35:06.340
So in the book I'm writing now,
the opening mystery is,

00:35:06.340 --> 00:35:11.660
why do court experts get it
wrong far more often than

00:35:11.660 --> 00:35:14.430
other sorts of scientists?

00:35:14.430 --> 00:35:16.920
And that's the mystery that's
leading me into a whole bunch

00:35:16.920 --> 00:35:20.270
of incredibly interesting
areas, I think.

00:35:20.270 --> 00:35:21.560
And yeah, you have to be open.

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:28.415
Not polemical, just open to
wherever the story takes you.

00:35:28.415 --> 00:35:28.858
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:35:28.858 --> 00:35:29.750
JON RONSON: Hi.

00:35:29.750 --> 00:35:30.610
AUDIENCE: Thank you
for coming.

00:35:30.610 --> 00:35:32.550
JON RONSON: Thank you.

00:35:32.550 --> 00:35:37.190
AUDIENCE: So the thing I
wonder-- you gave an example

00:35:37.190 --> 00:35:39.190
while talking about
your book--

00:35:39.190 --> 00:35:44.070
is talking to these people and
confronting them about this

00:35:44.070 --> 00:35:45.960
classification of
their behavior.

00:35:48.700 --> 00:35:53.650
I think if I were to do that,
I would panic, like you did

00:35:53.650 --> 00:35:59.200
coming down from upstate
New York, every time.

00:35:59.200 --> 00:36:02.490
So how, as a person with
generalized anxiety disorder,

00:36:02.490 --> 00:36:05.410
how did you manage to do that?

00:36:05.410 --> 00:36:06.640
JON RONSON: Well, you know what
I think the answer is?

00:36:06.640 --> 00:36:07.980
And this is true for
people I know--

00:36:07.980 --> 00:36:09.520
I've got loved ones
who have OCD.

00:36:09.520 --> 00:36:11.740
And I think it's absolutely
the same.

00:36:11.740 --> 00:36:14.610
The weird truth of it is-- and
I'm sure this isn't true for

00:36:14.610 --> 00:36:17.530
everybody, with any kind of
anxiety disorder, but I think

00:36:17.530 --> 00:36:18.750
it's true for a lot
of people--

00:36:18.750 --> 00:36:20.450
which is that the anxiety always
manifests itself in

00:36:20.450 --> 00:36:22.380
completely irrational ways.

00:36:22.380 --> 00:36:25.910
And in real life frightening
situations, just

00:36:25.910 --> 00:36:27.750
like everyone else.

00:36:27.750 --> 00:36:32.120
You know, you analyze--

00:36:32.120 --> 00:36:35.520
what risk am I actually
in, here?

00:36:35.520 --> 00:36:39.872
And work it out, in a kind of
completely rational way.

00:36:39.872 --> 00:36:43.620
But you can't let your bloody
dog off the leash in Central

00:36:43.620 --> 00:36:45.520
Park because of an irrational
fear it's

00:36:45.520 --> 00:36:47.440
going to get run over.

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:48.850
So that's the truth of it.

00:36:48.850 --> 00:36:52.680
It's that anxiety disorders tend
to manifest themselves in

00:36:52.680 --> 00:36:56.110
irrational ways that don't
actually have any resemblance

00:36:56.110 --> 00:36:57.210
to reality.

00:36:57.210 --> 00:37:00.120
And when you're in genuine
anxiety-inducing situations,

00:37:00.120 --> 00:37:01.350
you're fine.

00:37:01.350 --> 00:37:04.615
Don't ask me why, but that
seems to be the case.

00:37:04.615 --> 00:37:07.480
AUDIENCE: And I've also been
asked to ask if you know if

00:37:07.480 --> 00:37:08.730
Tony's still in Broadmoor.

00:37:08.730 --> 00:37:09.430
JON RONSON: Well, OK.

00:37:09.430 --> 00:37:10.040
I--

00:37:10.040 --> 00:37:11.710
I--

00:37:11.710 --> 00:37:13.550
