sale up there, or is it just

00:37:13.550 --> 00:37:14.290
"Lost at Sea?"

00:37:14.290 --> 00:37:15.010
PRESENTER: Just "Lost at Sea."

00:37:15.010 --> 00:37:15.320
JON RONSON: OK.

00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:17.845
In that case, does anybody mind
if I sort of give away

00:37:17.845 --> 00:37:19.690
what happened to Tony?

00:37:19.690 --> 00:37:24.130
The book's still fine anyway,
even if you know the ending.

00:37:24.130 --> 00:37:25.380
OK.

00:37:25.380 --> 00:37:31.500
Tony called me, and
for a while, I

00:37:31.500 --> 00:37:32.790
didn't take his calls.

00:37:32.790 --> 00:37:36.450
Because frankly I found
the label terrifying.

00:37:36.450 --> 00:37:38.590
And then after a while,
I took his calls.

00:37:38.590 --> 00:37:42.680
And he said, you know why
you've been calling me?

00:37:42.680 --> 00:37:45.140
And I said, because they said
that you're a psychopath.

00:37:45.140 --> 00:37:47.380
And he said, look, I'm
not a psychopath.

00:37:47.380 --> 00:37:49.435
And he said, trying to prove
you're not a psychopath is

00:37:49.435 --> 00:37:51.270
even harder than trying to prove
you're not mentally ill,

00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:55.050
because one of the items on
the checklist is lack of

00:37:55.050 --> 00:37:57.970
remorse, and another one is
cunning, manipulative.

00:37:57.970 --> 00:38:01.360
So when I say I feel terrible
remorse for what I did, they

00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:04.850
say typical of a psychopathic
to cunningly say they feel

00:38:04.850 --> 00:38:06.110
remorse, when they don't.

00:38:06.110 --> 00:38:07.440
He said it's like witchcraft.

00:38:07.440 --> 00:38:09.240
They turn everything
upside down.

00:38:09.240 --> 00:38:11.230
And he said, anyway, I've
got a tribunal.

00:38:11.230 --> 00:38:14.060
And it actually was partly do
with me, I have to say,

00:38:14.060 --> 00:38:17.370
because before my book was
published, I told Tony's story

00:38:17.370 --> 00:38:20.580
on "This American Life," and
it had a bit of an impact.

00:38:20.580 --> 00:38:26.280
And Tony sent it to various
lawyers and got himself a

00:38:26.280 --> 00:38:28.840
tribunal, in part, I think,
because of the publicity

00:38:28.840 --> 00:38:31.590
because of "This
American Life."

00:38:31.590 --> 00:38:33.000
And he got a tribunal.

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:35.550
And in the tribunal,
they let him go.

00:38:35.550 --> 00:38:38.560
He'd been in Broadmoor
for 14 years by then.

00:38:38.560 --> 00:38:41.030
12 years in Broadmoor, two years
at the Maudsley, which

00:38:41.030 --> 00:38:42.270
is a similar place.

00:38:42.270 --> 00:38:48.215
And they let him go because they
said that you shouldn't

00:38:48.215 --> 00:38:51.060
be locked up for the rest of
your life because you score

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:53.100
highly on a checklist
that would imply a

00:38:53.100 --> 00:38:55.800
greater-than-average
recidivism rate.

00:38:55.800 --> 00:38:57.830
It's almost kind of Orwellian.

00:38:57.830 --> 00:39:04.340
And out in the corridor, Tony
came up to me, and he said,

00:39:04.340 --> 00:39:07.560
you've got to realize, Jon, that
everybody's a little bit

00:39:07.560 --> 00:39:08.770
psychopathic.

00:39:08.770 --> 00:39:12.006
He said, you are, I am--
well, obviously, I am.

00:39:12.006 --> 00:39:13.780
And I said, what are you
going to do now?

00:39:13.780 --> 00:39:15.910
He said, there's this
woman in Belgium I

00:39:15.910 --> 00:39:17.940
fancy, but she's married.

00:39:17.940 --> 00:39:20.910
And I'm going to have to get her
split up from her husband.

00:39:20.910 --> 00:39:22.935
But you know what they say
about us psychopaths.

00:39:22.935 --> 00:39:24.450
We are manipulative.

00:39:24.450 --> 00:39:28.970
And then he disappeared off
into the British night.

00:39:28.970 --> 00:39:34.140
And everything was fine
for about six months.

00:39:34.140 --> 00:39:36.530
Brian, the Scientologist, would
give me updates, and he

00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:38.190
was making up for lost time.

00:39:38.190 --> 00:39:40.150
Which I know sounds
ominous, but

00:39:40.150 --> 00:39:42.180
wasn't necessarily ominous.

00:39:42.180 --> 00:39:45.410
That he got into a bar fight
and ended up going

00:39:45.410 --> 00:39:46.580
to jail for a month.

00:39:46.580 --> 00:39:52.330
As part of the release, part of
the probation, he couldn't

00:39:52.330 --> 00:39:54.180
go back to the mental
hospital.

00:39:54.180 --> 00:39:56.280
He had to be treated by
the prison system.

00:39:56.280 --> 00:39:58.930
And by the way, the unit he was
in closed down, because

00:39:58.930 --> 00:40:01.790
the government actually began
to think the same thoughts

00:40:01.790 --> 00:40:04.960
about the DSPD unit.

00:40:04.960 --> 00:40:07.070
So the unit closed down.

00:40:07.070 --> 00:40:08.090
So he went to jail
for a month.

00:40:08.090 --> 00:40:10.930
Then he came out.

00:40:10.930 --> 00:40:14.220
And that's the last I heard
until about two weeks ago,

00:40:14.220 --> 00:40:18.560
when I got a tweet from somebody
in a bookstore, who

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:22.110
said that somebody in the
bookstore had said that he was

00:40:22.110 --> 00:40:25.280
one of Tony's care workers,
and they'd got

00:40:25.280 --> 00:40:26.650
talking about it.

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:28.640
He was back in prison.

00:40:28.640 --> 00:40:29.690
So I looked him up--

00:40:29.690 --> 00:40:33.330
I'm one of the few people who
know his actual name.

00:40:33.330 --> 00:40:39.800
And sure enough, he had racially
assaulted a station

00:40:39.800 --> 00:40:44.220
guard somewhere just outside
London, and had gone back to

00:40:44.220 --> 00:40:44.740
prison for--

00:40:44.740 --> 00:40:46.130
I don't know how long.

00:40:46.130 --> 00:40:47.510
I think maybe a few months.

00:40:47.510 --> 00:40:48.920
And that's the last
I've heard.

00:40:48.920 --> 00:40:51.050
So it's not a happy ending.

00:40:55.060 --> 00:40:56.750
Which by the way--
let me just say.

00:40:56.750 --> 00:40:58.540
It then begs the question,
well, is it right

00:40:58.540 --> 00:40:59.670
that Tony was out?

00:40:59.670 --> 00:41:04.370
And it's a very difficult
question, but I still think,

00:41:04.370 --> 00:41:07.640
yes, it was, for all the
obvious reasons.

00:41:07.640 --> 00:41:09.630
AUDIENCE: It seems like there's
sort of a movement

00:41:09.630 --> 00:41:12.900
towards thinking that people who
have mental disorders that

00:41:12.900 --> 00:41:17.500
have, you know, psychopathy or
things like that, should be

00:41:17.500 --> 00:41:21.560
treated as criminals or
dangerous and locked up.

00:41:21.560 --> 00:41:23.200
What do you think about that?

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:25.030
JON RONSON: Well, this
is the big thing.

00:41:25.030 --> 00:41:26.370
And it's a huge thing in
America at the moment.

00:41:26.370 --> 00:41:28.850
There's these places
for pedophiles.

00:41:28.850 --> 00:41:33.240
There's one in Los Angeles
called Coalinga, where the day

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:37.530
somebody's done their time and
is released from jail, they

00:41:37.530 --> 00:41:39.480
immediately get sent to
Coalinga, and they're locked

00:41:39.480 --> 00:41:41.240
up, kind of, for the rest
of their lives.

00:41:41.240 --> 00:41:43.010
Because once you're in
that nexus, it's

00:41:43.010 --> 00:41:44.460
impossible to get out.

00:41:44.460 --> 00:41:47.660
And there was a story in "The
Los Angeles Times" where one

00:41:47.660 --> 00:41:50.980
of the doctors at Coalinga has
said a huge percentage of the

00:41:50.980 --> 00:41:53.780
people there shouldn't
be there.

00:41:53.780 --> 00:41:57.880
And Robert Hare said that the
people who determine who is

00:41:57.880 --> 00:42:00.950
and isn't a psychopathic on
behalf of Coalinga, he said he

00:42:00.950 --> 00:42:04.420
teaches them, and they're just
picking their nails, and

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:05.730
they're doodling.

00:42:05.730 --> 00:42:07.510
And they're going to go off and
kind of have a huge effect

00:42:07.510 --> 00:42:08.460
on people's lives.

00:42:08.460 --> 00:42:10.700
So on balance, even though
there's no question that

00:42:10.700 --> 00:42:12.660
psychopaths exist, and there's
no question that they're

00:42:12.660 --> 00:42:15.370
incredibly problematic, and
that they'll reoffend and

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:23.410
reoffend and reoffend, it's
still really hard, it's still

00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:26.670
a real problem to think, well,
OK, lock them up for the rest

00:42:26.670 --> 00:42:27.610
of their lives.

00:42:27.610 --> 00:42:30.080
It feels wrong, right?

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:33.920
So I feel that you just have
to take your chances.

00:42:33.920 --> 00:42:36.510
Lock them up for the amount of
time that each individual

00:42:36.510 --> 00:42:40.730
crime deserved, because the
alternative is worse.

00:42:40.730 --> 00:42:42.050
But you know, I mean,
what do I know?

00:42:42.050 --> 00:42:46.520
This is like three, four years
of my life, and that's the

00:42:46.520 --> 00:42:48.100
conclusion I came to.

00:42:48.100 --> 00:42:50.170
But it's not an easy topic.

00:42:53.600 --> 00:42:55.050
Please can we not end on that?

00:42:55.050 --> 00:42:58.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:58.240 --> 00:43:01.955
JON RONSON: Maybe we
can end on that.

00:43:01.955 --> 00:43:04.730
I've been told I can see rooms
at Google that people don't

00:43:04.730 --> 00:43:07.730
get to go to, so that's
exciting.

