AUDIENCE: We can't comment
about [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:40.810 --> 00:43:42.790
hummingbirds.

00:43:42.790 --> 00:43:47.461
So there's a suggestion that 1%
of people are psychopaths.

00:43:47.461 --> 00:43:49.766
Have they done a big enough
population sampling for that

00:43:49.766 --> 00:43:51.050
to be reasonable?

00:43:51.050 --> 00:43:54.310
JON RONSON: I've got to say,
this is completely subjective.

00:43:54.310 --> 00:43:56.180
Hare is absolutely adamant
that that's

00:43:56.180 --> 00:43:58.110
the percentage, 1%.

00:43:58.110 --> 00:44:02.530
And Hare is like a very
respected, eminent person.

00:44:02.530 --> 00:44:04.060
I've always thought
that sounds a bit

00:44:04.060 --> 00:44:05.580
high, I have to say.

00:44:05.580 --> 00:44:08.550
AUDIENCE: The thing is, if it
skews, I don't know, white,

00:44:08.550 --> 00:44:11.430
and it skews male,
and it basically

00:44:11.430 --> 00:44:13.530
skews living in America--

00:44:13.530 --> 00:44:17.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:19.980
AUDIENCE: Those numbers
seem atomically high.

00:44:19.980 --> 00:44:22.660
If it's 1%, and you're
up at 5% of all--

00:44:22.660 --> 00:44:23.410
JON RONSON: CEOs.

00:44:23.410 --> 00:44:24.890
It seems high, I've
got to tell you.

00:44:24.890 --> 00:44:26.345
I mean, Hare is very--

00:44:29.790 --> 00:44:30.750
he is cautious.

00:44:30.750 --> 00:44:33.090
I mean, I did have my slight
issues with him.

00:44:33.090 --> 00:44:37.480
There was this time-- and
I put this in the book--

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:41.940
when I met him at a
hotel in Heathrow.

00:44:41.940 --> 00:44:44.040
And I was looking for
him everywhere.

00:44:44.040 --> 00:44:44.740
It was late at night.

00:44:44.740 --> 00:44:45.700
I couldn't find him.

00:44:45.700 --> 00:44:47.550
We arranged to meet.

00:44:47.550 --> 00:44:49.970
And I decided to go to the
concierge desk to phone his

00:44:49.970 --> 00:44:53.240
room, because the queue was
so long at the desk.

00:44:53.240 --> 00:44:55.160
And so I went to the concierge's
phone and pressed

00:44:55.160 --> 00:44:57.010
0 to get through to
the operator.

00:44:57.010 --> 00:44:59.080
And the concierge was kind of
storming toward me, going, put

00:44:59.080 --> 00:44:59.710
down my phone!

00:44:59.710 --> 00:45:02.820
And I said-- and he grabbed the
phone and slammed it down.

00:45:02.820 --> 00:45:04.980
And then I met Robert Hare,
and I said, you wouldn't

00:45:04.980 --> 00:45:06.630
believe what just happened.

00:45:06.630 --> 00:45:09.690
The concierge just grabbed the
phone off me, and it was quite

00:45:09.690 --> 00:45:10.310
frightening.

00:45:10.310 --> 00:45:13.322
And Robert Hare said, well,
that's because he's one.

00:45:13.322 --> 00:45:14.246
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:14.246 --> 00:45:15.632
And I said, really?

00:45:15.632 --> 00:45:18.310
And he said, you should
put that in your book.

00:45:18.310 --> 00:45:20.480
And I said, I will.

00:45:20.480 --> 00:45:21.760
So I mean, I agree.

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:25.210
This is something I don't say
very often, because I have a

00:45:25.210 --> 00:45:27.700
lot of respect for Robert
Hare, and I really do.

00:45:27.700 --> 00:45:30.170
And I think his checklist
is onto something.

00:45:30.170 --> 00:45:35.065
But I've always thought
1% seems high.

00:45:35.065 --> 00:45:36.315
Yeah.

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:38.970
OK.

00:45:38.970 --> 00:45:40.990
Well, look, well, thank you.

00:45:40.990 --> 00:45:41.760
Thank you very much indeed.

00:45:41.760 --> 00:45:42.960
And happy Christmas.

